Brane running and AdS/CFT 


Michele Redi(email: redi@pha.jhu.edu)  


Department of Physics and Astronomy  

Johns Hopkins University  

3400 North Charles St . 

Baltimore, MD 21218-2686   

 
 

 
We extend the formalism introduced in the paper hep-th/0209050 to
compute correlation functions in the AdS/CFT correspondence. We show how the
on-shell action of a scalar field in a compactification of AdS space can
be obtained by flowing in the space of (non-local) theories with
different sizes of the extra-dimension. Our method is relevant in
particular for holographic computations in the Randall-Sundrum
scenario with one or two branes and it allows the inclusion of brane-localized
actions in a systematic way. The method can also be
generalized to other backgrounds and does not rely on explicit
knowledge of the solutions of the wave-equations.


Introduction 
The full dynamical content of the AdS/CFT correspondence (for a review)
can be summarized by an
equivalence between two path integrals,:
 
Here  represents the fields propagating on Anti-de Sitter space (AdS) and  are the
dual gauge invariant operators in the Conformal Field Theory (CFT).  is the
partition function on (Euclidian) AdS, computed with the boundary condition that
the field  approaches  at the boundary of AdS.
The right-hand side of () is the generating functional of the correlation functions
of the dual CFT living on the boundary  of AdS.
In the limit where classical field theory is a good description of the
physics on AdS (corresponding to the large  limit and large 't Hooft parameter on the CFT side),
 
where  is the on-shell value of the classical action for fields that
satisfy the condition  at the boundary of AdS.
In order to compute  typically one first reconstructs, using the classical
equations of motion, the on-shell value of  with the required boundary behavior
and then substitute in the action. This can be done iteratively using
bulk-to-boundary and bulk-to-bulk propagators.

The goal of this paper will be to show how to compute  using
the method of brane running. In principle, no explicit knowledge of bulk-to-boundary
an bulk-to-bulk propagators is required.
This approach was originally proposed in and extended in to gauge fields and gravity,
to compute effective field theories of a brane-localized observer in the Randall-Sundrum
scenario with two branes (RS1).
As in that paper, we will consider the compactification of AdS on an orbifold  with fixed
points at  (the ultraviolet brane) and at  (the infrared brane), where  is the radial coordinate of AdS.
In the context of the full AdS/CFT correspondence, this geometry should be simply regarded as a regularization:
the  brane modifies AdS near the boundary and the  brane cuts the space in the direction of the horizon.
In the RS1 scenario instead, two physical branes placed at the fixed points, end the space.
In the authors were interested in computing effective theories of an observer localized
on the  brane, while here we will use the brane running method to compute the on-shell action
as a function of the fields at .

The basic idea is that the dependence of the on-shell value of the action on the fields
at  can be obtained integrating out bulk degrees of freedom.
Specifically, we consider theories with
different locations of the  brane. Effective brane actions are generated which guarantee that
 does not change. By moving the  brane up to ,
by construction  equals the effective  brane action. Using (),
the couplings of the effective  brane action can be identified with the correlation functions of the CFT.
The couplings on the effective brane "run" in a way
that resembles an ordinary renormalization group (RG) flow. In particular, in the limit where the physical  brane
is at infinity, corresponding to the RS2 scenario, all the brane couplings flow to a non-local fixed point.
Notice that the running of the brane couplings should be not be
confused with the RG flow of the observables in
the dual field theory (see for example), since we are keeping the cutoff, represented by the
location of  brane, fixed.

This formalism appears particularly appropriate for computations in the RS1
scenario. In the holographic interpretation, this model is dual to
a CFT with a cutoff , where conformal invariance is also broken
in the infrared by the  brane at the energy scale .
Since conformal invariance is broken, the couplings on the effective brane
are now not at their fixed points but,
at energies , we can consider this as a small deviation from
conformality. Brane actions can be included with ease, they simply modify the initial
condition for the flow at .

The paper is organized as follows. In Section  we present the
general techniques in the case of the point function of a scalar field and
reproduce well known results.
In Section  we extend the procedure to  and
point functions and consider the general structure of higher-point functions.
In Section  we apply the brane running method to holographic computations
in the RS1 model. Section  contains the conclusions.
A more detailed analysis of the point function is left to
the Appendix.

