Applications 
In this section we apply the brane running method
to the Randall-Sundrum scenario
. We take .

In the full AdS/CFT correspondence, a theory on AdS is
equivalent to a pure conformal field theory living on the
boundary. In the previous analysis the  brane and the  brane
should be understood as regulators of the theory so the physical
quantities are extracted in the limit  and 
. As we have argued, the second limit (corresponding to the geometry
of the RS2 model) implies that all the
couplings on the effective brane are at their fixed points.
In the RS1 scenario, five dimensional AdS
is truncated by two physical branes parallel to the boundary,
placed at the fixed points of an orbifold. Since small values of
the coordinate  correspond to the ultraviolet of the CFT, the presence of the
 brane represents a cutoff applied to the CFT. On the other
hand, the  brane modifies the space only at large  so naively it
corresponds, in the holographic picture, to breaking
(spontaneously) conformal invariance in the infrared at a scale
. It should be clear from the present paper that this
conclusion may not hold when brane actions are included: theories with
different size of the extra-dimension can have the same CFT dual.
Since for phenomenological applications one takes
, the theory should appear
approximately conformal for a large range of energies, namely
.

To any order in the fields, the dependence of the action on the
boundary values of the fields can be computed integrating the flow
equations presented in the previous sections. This can be done
perturbatively in  as shown in the Appendix for the point
function. In particular it is straightforward, even for higher-point functions,
to compute the zero momentum dependence of the
coupling . The leading dependence on the external
momentum is also not hard to compute. Since the  brane breaks
conformal invariance in the infrared, the brane couplings are not at
a fixed point, but acquire an explicit dependence on the
scale .

In the case of the point function, equation
() can be solved explicitly, the solution being:
 
The integration constant  is determined by the boundary condition
at the  brane, namely . This allows
the inclusion in a simple and systematic way of arbitrary brane
actions. For example, for a massless scalar and , corresponding to
ordinary Neumann boundary condition, the result is:
 
For  this is just the analytic continuation to Euclidean AdS of the
inverse of the brane-to-brane propagator of a massless scalar
computed in. In general,
 is the inverse of the brane-to-brane propagator, so
the zeros in  of  correspond
to the masses of the Kaluza-Klein (KK) modes.

For  one can expand  in powers of . The
expansion is now completely polynomial in momentum. Technically
this happens because if the boundary condition is local, this
property will be preserved by the flow. From the CFT point of view,
this fact is simply the statement that below the scale ,
conformal symmetry is completely broken, and in particular, a mass
gap is generated. On the AdS side we have a discrete set of
 particles whose mass scale is set by .
This discrete set of particles gives rise
to isolated poles in the propagator but no branch cuts. Therefore,
at energies below the masses of the KK modes, this system should be
describable in terms of a local action.

At energies above
, conformal invariance is approximately restored. For
, i.e. energies below the cutoff of the CFT, we can
expand  around . In the case of the massless scalar () we have:
 
In the limit  we recover the expansion of the
fixed point. This should be expected since in this limit all
the couplings flow to their fixed points. Using the asymptotic expansion
of the Bessel functions, it is easy to see that the deviation
from  becomes exponentially small at energies greater that . Since for
large momenta the presence of the  brane represents a small
deviation from conformality, all the brane couplings are close to the
fixed point. In this regime it is useful to simplify the flow equation
expanding to linear order around :
 
where . To leading order, for , the
solution of the previous equation is simply  independently on .
As we move the effective brane to smaller ,  becomes exponentially suppressed.
Similar manipulations can be done for higher-point functions.

Localized fields can be naturally included in this
formalism. This case is important for phenomenological
applications. For example, in the original proposal by Randall and
Sundrum, in order to solve the hierarchy problem, the Standard
Model fields were localized on the  brane. For fields
localized on the  brane, it is obvious that their action should
be added to the effective action. From the CFT point of
view, fields living on the  brane are interpreted as fields
external to the CFT and coupled to the gauge invariant operators
of the CFT. Therefore, it is natural to add the action of the CFT and that
of the external fields. In the case of fields localized on the  brane,
or in the bulk, the analysis is more intricate because
these fields couple only indirectly to the  brane. As an
example, following, we consider a free scalar
field coupled to an external source  localized at . In  dimensions, the
AdS action contains:
 
Consistency requires the brane action:
 
The running of  is given by:
 
while the function of  remains unchanged. Notice that only
in this particular case a coupling depends on higher order ones.(If bulk
interactions are included the function of the coupling
 will depend on the couplings up to .) 
For a localized source in the case where the  brane is at infinity,
 will still be
at its fixed point (). It is not hard to check that the
solution of () is:
 
A tadpole for the field  is generated in the effective field
theory of an observer on the  brane. On the CFT side, this
corresponds to an expectation value for the dual operator.

Conclusions and Outlook 
In this paper we have shown how to compute the value of the on-shell
AdS action of a scalar field by flowing in the space of
theories with a different size for the extra-dimension. By
integrating out bulk degrees of freedom, we generate effective
brane actions which reproduce exactly the same physics in the
restricted region. To any order in the fields, the dependence of the on-shell action on the
boundary value of the fields at  is obtained by solving the flow
equations for the couplings on the effective brane.
In principle, this procedure does not require the
knowledge of the bulk-to-boundary and bulk-to-bulk propagators.
The values of the couplings are related in a simple way to the
correlation functions of the CFT. In the case of infinite AdS or RS2, the
brane couplings are at their fixed points, corresponding to an unbroken
CFT.

This formalism is particularly appropriate for holographic
computations in the RS1 model. Here the
couplings on the effective brane are not at the fixed points but
acquire an explicit dependence on the radial coordinate. At energies much
above the scale set by the  brane, corresponding to the scale
where conformal invariance is broken, the couplings are very close
to the fixed points so we can simplify the flow equations.

Gauge fields and fluctuations of the metric can be included
in a very similar way. The relevant steps are presented in
, where the brane running is used to compute
the effective field theory of an observer living on the 
brane. The extension to fermionic fields is non-trivial because the
wave-equation is a first order differential equation in this case.

More in general, the method of brane running can be used in geometries
which contain a Poincare invariant subspace.
The structure of the  functions for the
couplings would be similar to the one in the present paper. In
this case though, the brane couplings, even in the infinite space
limit, will not be at a fixed point.

